body:
According to the [docs](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/std/fs/fn.remove_dir.html) for `remove_dir`:

```
This function will return an error in the following situations, but is not limited to just these cases:

    path doesn’t exist.
    path isn’t a directory.
    The user lacks permissions to remove the directory at the provided path.
    The directory isn’t empty.
```

I expected `remove_dir` to fail when removing read only directories. However, it succeeds on linux when the folder's mode is `444` (aka read only). Running the `rm -r <folder>` command fails on similarly configured directories.

```
timothy@yoga /tmp$ mkdir foo
timothy@yoga /tmp$ chmod 444 foo
timothy@yoga /tmp$ rm -r foo
rm: remove write-protected directory 'foo'? y
```

Here is a failing test case:

```
    #[test]
    fn test_remove_dir() {
        use std::fs::set_permissions;
        use std::fs::Permissions;
        use std::os::unix::fs::PermissionsExt;
        use tempdir::TempDir;
        use std::fs::remove_dir;
        let tmp_dir = TempDir::new("test_parent_dir").unwrap();
        let unwritable_dir = tmp_dir.path().join("unwritable-dir");
        fs::create_dir(unwritable_dir.clone()).unwrap();
        let ro_permissions: Permissions = Permissions::from_mode(0o444);
        match set_permissions(unwritable_dir.clone(), ro_permissions) {
            Ok(_) => assert!(true),
            Err(_) => assert!(false),
        };
        match remove_dir(unwritable_dir.clone()){
            Ok(_) => assert!(false),
            Err(e) => assert_eq!(e.to_string(), "Permission denied (os error 13)"),
        };
        let normal_permissions: Permissions = Permissions::from_mode(0o644);
        set_permissions(unwritable_dir.clone(), normal_permissions).unwrap();
        assert_eq!(fs::read_dir(tmp_dir).unwrap().count(), 1);
    }
```

Here is the output of the test:

```
